As we all know, as the years passed Tolkien began to worry about the fact
that Orcs seemed to be irredeemably evil, since such a concept contradicted
his Catholic faith. Whereas he earlier had been content to say that the
question was irrelevant since they were only creatures in a fairy-story, he
now tried to devise various ways to evade having irredeemably evil, sentient
beings in his books. One of his suggested solutions was that the Orcs were
simply soulless automatons. However, from what we see of the Orcs in LotR,
it is very hard to perceive them as so depersonalized . There is also this
statement by Gorbag in &quot;The Choices of Master Samwise&quot;:

&quot;Grr! Those Nazgûl give me the creeps. And they skin the body off you as
soon as look at you, and leave all cold in the dark on the other side&quot;.

To met, that sounds like a definite statement about a soul that can be
separated from the body.
Of course, I think Tolkien could have got out of the trap by simply saying
that it was quite possible that after death, Orcs were given a second chance
and sent to some kind of purgatory.

Öjevind
