Part of the problem is the question: what were the Orcs?

Some Orcs, in particular their &quot;great captains&quot; were, at times, stated
or implied to be embodied Maiar.

In some conceptions, Orcs were made from stone. If this sounds like
something that would be said of Dwarves, well, yes, it was said of
Dwarves and survived (for Dwarves) as an erroneous belief of Men.

The dominant conception was that Orcs were perversions of Elves and/or
Men. This, of course, reflected the determination that even the
mightiest Vala could not actually create life (note that the Dwarves
were created by Aule and given life by Eru).

Actually, whether the Orcs derived from Men is unclear: if Orcs
appeared before Men appeared, then that seems unlikely, although
Orc-Man matings might have been treated as Orcs.

If Orcs are perverted Elves, then their fear are Elven fear and, after
the death of the body, they go to Mandos (Elvish section) were they
are, indeed, subject to purgation, much as Feanor, but perhaps longer.

If Orcs are perverted Men, then they should share the fate of Men,
whatever that may be. If there is a purgatory for Men, it is beyond
the Wall of Night, and so the Orcs would go there as well.

If Orcs are perverted mixes of Elf and Man, then they should be
treated as Elves. It might be thought they had a choice, but Elwing
had no choice, her brothers had no choice, Dior Thingol's Heir had no
choice: choice of Elf or Man appears to be limited to Elros, Elrond,
and Elrond's children.

I do not doubt that JRRT was bothered by this problem. But, as I have
said before, he presumably believed that God provided souls to people
like Hitler and Stalin, and so should not have been bothered by the
idea that Eru provided fear to Orcs -- who in /The Hobbit/ and /LOTR/
are depicted as clearly lower-class, crude in speech and habits,
forming the worst sort of army to be in, desirous of slipping away and
founding their own very petty little totalitarian states.
--
&quot;He who should know the history of words
would know all history&quot;
