That's not necessarily true.

&quot;'My dear tender little fools,' hissed Grishnakh, 'everything you have,
and everything you know, will be got out of you in due time: everything!
You'll wish there was more that you could tell to satisfy the Questioner,
indeed you will: quite soon! We shan't hurry the enquiry. Oh dear no! What
do you think you've been kept alive for? My dear little fellows, please
believe me when I say that it was not out of kindness: that's not even one
of Ugluk's faults.'&quot;

This is not just grammatically correct; it's practically public-school.
Note the usages like 'shan't' and 'my dear little fellows,' as well as the
Brit-nob circumlocution 'please believe me when I tell you.' This is not
working-class at all: one could almost imagine Grishnakh stroking a white
Angora cat!

If anything could be said to characterize this speech it's that it is
*modern*- a very 20th-century idiom: and Tolkien seemed to like playing
with modern faux-politeness and language affectations wrapping evil
intent, as with Smaug, Chrysophylax, and that Ur-modernist Saruman.

In fact, reviewing the chapter /The Uruk-hai/, I see nothing in the speech
of Isengarders, Northerners, or the Lugburz contingent which can be marked
as 'lower-class.' Shagrat and Gorbag are slightly more slang-y, but
nowhere near as colloquial as the rural Hobbits.  The only Orc we meet, in
fact, whose speech comes across as remotely 'debased and corrupted' is the
tracker, Snaga, who is lower-class even by Orc standards- and his diction
isn't shared by his big Uruk companion.

I'm amused frankly by one critic who went on about &quot;Cockney&quot; Orcs,
&quot;dropped Aitches and all&quot;....when in fact there is not one single elided H
or deformed vowel-sound anywhere in Tolkien's Orc-speech- the fact that
the critic *heard* them that way with his mental ear says rather more
about the critic's class-assumptions than Tolkien's!

