You know, there's a part of the Fate and Free Will thread that might bear
on this (for us; I don't think it occurred to JRRT).  Remember where
Aquinas in the Summa concludes that men are incapable of even the least
good act but for Divine grace?  St Tom then goes on of course to argue
that therefore some level of grace is available to all, since even pagans
and unbelievers plainly do behave virtuously.

But what if we explored the other fork of the argument?  Shippey has
pointed out that Orcs clearly do have a moral sense- they have a set of
values which most would agree are 'good:' but apparently *always* fail to
act upon them.

Could Orcs therefore be seen as those who are utterly without Divine
grace, and therefore incapable of the least good action?

Mythologically, I suppose, one might see the Orcs as having been descended
from those Men who were first seduced by the Dark, and went deepest into
its service; perhaps its priests and Levites, the one who seized others
for thaie sacrifices: their condemnation was thus even worse than that
accorded to other Men, their dupes and victims. These Men were denied any
scrap of Grace: whereas Men (in M-E and, to a Catholic, in our world) have
an inborn propensity to sin, these Men &gt; Orcs would be *guaranteed* to
sin, at all times. (After all, as a Catholic Tolkien *shouldn't* have had
a problem with the heritability of sin!)

