At some point in the past, I was pointed to a bit of Aquinas on-line
in which &quot;building a house&quot; was given as an example of &quot;a good deed&quot;.

Consider the Goblins in the Hobbit: have they not created, if not a
house, then at least a home? They have a society, a warm fire, a food
supply and, for all we know, women and children. (Actually, we /do/
know they have children hanging around -- we are told that Gollum ate
them when he could catch them -- and so they must have had women there
as well). Would these not be &quot;good things&quot; requiring some measure of
grace?

Most of the Orcs we encounter close-up in LOTR are in military
service, which is why they are all male (at the time it was written,
this was very nearly true of most of our armies). While I suspect that
non-military Orc culture was rather crude, the military version
appears to move beyond crude into nasty. And yet, even in this
context, the fact that lower-ranking Orcs follow orders [1] (at least
some of them, some of the time) is, in military terms, a &quot;good thing&quot;
-- again requiring some measure of grace.

Note that this has nothing to do with the dialect of English used to
portray their speech. It has to do rather with the content of their
speech -- and so with the content of their thought.

I think JRRT just thought himself into a box on this point, and could
not find his way out again.

[1] Indeed, the mere fact that they recognized that they were supposed
to follow orders is a &quot;good thing&quot;, and the fact that some of them
fought others on whether or not to do so or whose orders to follow is
even more of a &quot;good thing&quot;.
