The problem is that Lenin and Stalin were not _born_ evil.  It's a
given that they _could_ have been different, they could have made
different choices, followed other paths.

The problem of the Orcs is that they appear to have been corrupted _as
a race_.  It's not hard to imagine that Morgorth might sway ancient
Elves to his service, leading them into evil.  But the idea that Eru
would provide souls to creatures _born_ evil runs directly counter to
Christian thinking and to the theological framework of Tolkein's
stories.

The problem has no easy solution.

Changing Orcs from corrupt Elves to corrupt Men?  No effect at all on
the moral/theological aspect.

Making orcs into biological automata?  That fixes the theological
problem, but is utterly unbelievable in the context of the stories.
Ugluk, Grishnakh, Shagrat and Gorbag, etc, all showed too much free
will for that to fly.  They even have a moral sense, as famously noted
when they refer to abandoning one's comrades as an 'Elvish sort of
trick'.

No question about it, in my mind from readin LOTR and _The Hobbit_,
Orcs are people too.
