Actually, it comes to the same thing, at least in my understanding of
Aquinas.

Aquinas agrees with Aristotle that &quot;man always chooses the good&quot;.
Well, provided the particular individual is sane, of course; the
insane may make other choices; but discussions of man in general
generally deal only with sane people. The problem is that what man
actually chooses is what he /perceives/ as good -- and his perception
is corrupted by original sin. Man thus believes that he is choosing
the good but, without grace, is in fact always choosing evil. The
/effect/ of original sin is that man, without grace, always chooses
evil even though he believes that he is choosing good. It is in this
sense that man can be said to be born evil. It should be kept in mind
that &quot;evil&quot; is defined as &quot;absence of good&quot;; &quot;evil&quot; has no positive
definition.

Attempts to assert otherwise are invariably refuted by Aquinas, who
identifies them with one or another of the historically-identified
heresies condemned by the various councils (which he cites).

For example, Aquinas speaks of man, in his natural state, that is,
before the Fall, as having complete control over his body and as
having lost this in the Fall. But this is not to be interpreted as
meaning that the body is corrupt and the soul is still pure; that is
heresy, particularly when the conclusion is drawn that the soul is
being punished by being placed in the body. Rather, the situation is
that the soul is corrupt and, as a result, no longer controls the
body. (Another way of putting this, not necessarily Thomistic or even
RC, is that, just as the soul is in rebellion against God, so is the
body in rebellion against the soul).

In the same way, then, the soul is corrupted by original sin and can
no longer perceive the good -- and so the will can no longer choose
the good, but only what the mind believes to be good, which is, in
fact, evil. To assert that the unaided man can perceive good (and so
actually choose good) is also heresy; when fully developed, it becomes
Pelagianism.

Aquinas can be a bit confusing on this point because he often uses the
phrases such as &quot;man's nature as such&quot; (there are others) to refer to
the nature and status of man before the Fall. He usually continues on
to discuss the nature of man as it is today, which is after the Fall.
He can be quoted saying all sorts of things about man pre-Fall that
seem to contradict or ameliorate this position, but, in fact, none of
them apply to man as he is today.

Christians do not believe and never have believed that people are born
good and become evil by their own choice; this belief belongs to a
different philosophy. Christians do believe that people are born
sinful and therefore, left to their own devices, do evil as a result
of their own choices -- which has the same effect as saying that they
are born evil, when evil is defined as the absence of good. Some
Christians, as noted elsewhere, extend this viewpoint to total
depravity; however, as Niebuhr observes somewhere in /The Nature and
Destiny of Man/, no doubt phrased better, if man were totally
depraved, he would not be able to realize that he were depraved, and
he clearly is able to realize that he is depraved, so he cannot be
totally depraved.
