This illustrates the difficulty I have reading Aquinas: my background
is Lutheran, and so I must constantly struggle to understand what
Aquinas is saying, not what I think he is saying.

It also illustrates the way Aquinas' work builds on itself: God as
First Mover is part of the first Treatise (I A2): it is one of the
proofs of God's existence. I have noted in the past that the proof
does not seem to me to work because, even granting that it proves a
First Mover exists, it merely asserts that the First Mover is God:

&quot;Therefore it is necessary to arrive at a first mover, put in motion
by no other; and this everyone understands to be God.&quot;

Even if literally true when made, this simply is not the case today.

Yet here the other shoe drops, and God's status as First Mover is
cited to show that -- well, what does it show? Another use of God as
First Mover is (II-II A1):

&quot;Now every use implies movement, taking movement broadly, so as to
call thinking and willing movements, as is clear from the Philosopher
(De Anima iii, 4). Now in corporeal things we see that for movement
there is required not merely the form which is the principle of the
movement or action, but there is also required the motion of the first
mover. Now the first mover in the order of corporeal things is the
heavenly body. Hence no matter how perfectly fire has heat, it would
not bring about alteration, except by the motion of the heavenly body.
But it is clear that as all corporeal movements are reduced to the
motion of the heavenly body as to the first corporeal mover, so all
movements, both corporeal and spiritual, are reduced to the simple
First Mover, Who is God. And hence no matter how perfect a corporeal
or spiritual nature is supposed to be, it cannot proceed to its act
unless it be moved by God; but this motion is according to the plan of
His providence, and not by necessity of nature, as the motion of the
heavenly body.&quot;

I included the full context so that this part could be more easily
understood: &quot;all movements, both corporeal and spiritual, are reduced
to the simple First Mover, Who is God&quot;.

So, in Aquinas, man does /nothing whatsoever/ without the aid of God.

This is why I agreed, earlier in the thread, with the proposition that
God's grace must be presumed to be well-nigh universal, to some
extent, since nothing good can be done without it. Indeed, this
suggests that /nothing whatsoever/ can be done without, if not grace,
the aid of God. This assistance must underlie the ability to do the
&quot;particular good&quot; -- and so even the &quot;particular good&quot; cannot be done
by man acting alone, because man cannot act alone.

At least, it seems to me that that is what Aquinas is saying.

To move somewhat back on point: although JRRT clearly did have
problems with the idea of Eru providing Orcs with fear (souls), my
contention is that he should not have had any such problem, since, as
an RC, he should have known that God provided souls to men and women,
even to men who God must know would grow up to be monsters. I can now
expand this: JRRT should have realized that, to be consistent with the
rules of his own mythology, it was not possible for the Orcs to be
totally depraved and so irredeemable because they also, and, indeed
Morgoth himself, was unable to act without some aid from Eru. I think
he subjected himself to unnecessary doubts and worries by somehow
erring on this point.

This does presume that JRRT's understanding of RC was similar to that
of Aquinas. But whatever it was, the assertion (copied from above)
that

