I disagree.

Traditional Catholic doctrine holds that, had we complete knowledge
and understanding of the natural laws to whose working God has made
the universe subject, we would be able to predict all *physical*
events with certainty.  Yet, because God is by definition the highest
good and cannot therefore will evil, the *consequence* of the exercise
of free will is not willed by God, and therefore cannot be deduced
with reference to the natural laws he ordains for the universe.  The
choice between good and evil which one makes is therefore entirely and
completely one's own choice: God is aware of the choice each
individual will make (being omniscient) and allows it, but it is not,
and cannot be, a manifestation of his will; and the natural laws to
which God has subjected the universe therefore reveal nothing about
the choice an individual will make.

Yet, even if we do not know and cannot know what choice an individual
will make, we can and should know that the ultimate *outcome* will be
good, regardless of how many individuals choose evil.  This is because
of the idea Divine Providence - that God, despite sin and evil,
ultimately directs all things - even evil and sin - towards the
fulfilment of the purposes for which the universe was created.  Part
of &quot;faith&quot; (estel, in Tolkien's world) lies in trusting in Divine
Providence, even when it seems that evil and sin reign.

To my mind, it is this combination of natural determinism, free will
and Providence  - not moral determinism, and not predestination - that
the Music reflects.  The course of physical events is fully determined
by the laws ordained by God's will (the main theme of the Music).  The
sin and evil that infest the world are contrary to his purposes and
intention and do not reflect his will (the discords of Melkor) but are
permitted by him (Eru does not, for example, strike Melkor with a well-
aimed thunderbolt, as he easily could have).  And, ultimately, through
the agency of free will as exercised by the Eruhini (the third theme),
Arda will reach a fulfillment that is greater than what would
otherwise have been (the grand conclusion of the Music and the vision
of Arda Healed), to which even the sin and evil that has gone before
will have contributed (&quot;but it seemed that its most triumphant notes
were taken by the other and woven into its own solemn pattern&quot;).

--
