&gt;&gt; do otherwise. Therefore Free Will, in Tolkien's writings, does not
&gt;&gt; require that ability (that is independent of what we might think of
&gt;&gt; the matter of Free Will). Tolkien rather seems to have a view of Free
&gt;&gt; Will that is compatible with determinism and requires rather the
&gt;&gt; ability to act in a manner that is in accordance with one's true
&gt;&gt; self.
&gt; This antagonism between free will and the Music has always bothered
&gt; me. Surely it's obvious that the Ainur and the Elves do make choices.
&gt; We could argue, I suppose, that they only appear to make choices but
&gt; are actually constrained to act as they do, but then free will goes
&gt; out the window -- and with it goes responsibility for one's acts.
&gt; Somehow I have trouble reconciling that with what we know of
&gt; Tolkien's world view.

&gt; But I've just now been struck by a possible way out of the dilemma.

&gt; Suppose we think of the Music in a similar way to the laws of
&gt; physics. We do not see any conflict between free will and the fact
&gt; that I cannot choose to levitate.

&gt; So what would the music or Fate consist of? How would it govern Ainur
&gt; and Elves but not Men?

&gt; Is it as simple as this: that the Ainur and the Elves are constrained
&gt; by their nature to remain within Arda for all of its days, while Men
&gt; are not so constrained? That seems almost too simple, but at least it
&gt; preserves free will.

&gt; What I'm conjecturing, in other words, is that it was part of the
&gt; Music that the Firstborn and the Ainur would stay within Arda for its
&gt; whole life, but not Men. And when we say that the Music &quot;is as Fate&quot;
&gt; to all except Men, that's what we mean.

&gt; What do others think about these tentative thoughts?
">

It's a difficult philosphical question. I think there are several ways
out, but there will always be people who object or think differently.

I have the feeling that restricting the Music just to the fact that
Elves and Ainur have to stay in Arda takes away too much -- the Music
is also a parable for the &quot;plan&quot; that God has, and paradoxically
people will follow this plan, in the sense of &quot;thy will be done&quot;, even
if they retain their Free Will and the moral responsibility.

Personally, I have a different argument that allows me to reconcile
determinism (assuming a universe that is deterministic, or a variation
like the Music which implies some degree of determinism or &quot;fate&quot;),
and moral responsibility: Since the individual itself cannot actually
make use of the determinism and calculate the future, from the
viewpoint of the individual the choice as still made with Free
Will. Hence, the moral responsibility still lies with the
individual. From the outside, this choice will be deterministic, but
because the individual is what he or she is, this choice will reflect
their morality and Free Will. For me, that is enough, but I don't
expect many people will agree, and I won't try to defend this idea :-)

- Dirk
